Just throwing out a random idea that crossed my mind as I was testing the numpy handlers.

What if this:
```python
>>> jsonpickle.encode([b'a', b'b', b'c', b'd'])
[{
    "py/bytes": "a"
}, {
    "py/bytes": "b"
}, {
    "py/bytes": "c"
}, {
    "py/bytes": "d"
}]
```
could be instead encoded as something along the lines of:
```python
{
    "py/bytes": ["a", "b", "c", "d"]
}
```
And this:
```python
>>> from datetime import date
>>> jsonpickle.encode((date(2015, 1, 9), date(2015, 1, 10), date(2015, 1, 11)))
{
    "py/tuple": [{
        "py/object": "datetime.date",
        "__reduce__": [{
                "py/type": "datetime.date"
            },
            ["B98BCQ=="]
        ]
    }, {
        "py/object": "datetime.date",
        "__reduce__": [{
                "py/type": "datetime.date"
            },
            ["B98BCg=="]
        ]
    }, {
        "py/object": "datetime.date",
        "__reduce__": [{
                "py/type": "datetime.date"
            },
            ["B98BCw=="]
        ]
    }]
}
```
as
```python
{
    "py/date": {
        "py/tuple": ["2015-01-09", "2015-01-10", "2015-01-11"]
    }
}
```
This could not be the best/unambiguous way to encode this (e.g. what if it's a homegeneous tuple of tuples, or list of sets etc) but there are many other options so I'm sure it's possible to do this unambiguously if we want to, you get the point.

The benefits are: increased readability of the json output, more space-efficient representation of homogeneous sequences (in particular, more efficient encoding of numpy types which are always homogeneous for non-record arrays).

